William Butler Yeats was an Irish poet and playwright born in 1865 in Dublin, Ireland. He was one of the foremost figures of 20th century literature, known for his use of symbolism and mystical themes. Yeats received the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1923, in recognition of his significant contributions to poetry. Throughout his career, he wrote acclaimed works in both poetry and plays, drawing inspiration from Irish folklore and mythology as well as occult beliefs. Some of his most famous poems include "The Second Coming," "Lake Isle of Innisfree," and "Sailing to Byzantium." Yeats continued writing until his death in 1939, cementing his legacy as a master poet and dramatist.
